Event was one of many that will kick off a nationwide tour for Mickey, celebrating his 50th birthday, as well as the 75th anniversary of Hollywood.

(Published on 2/3/2019) As the region emerges from its coldest temperatures in years — with lows dipping down to minus 26 degrees Wednesday and Thursday — Saturday’s visitors to the annual Frozen Assets Festival enjoyed milder temperatures but contended with sloppy conditions on Lake Mendota. Hosted annually by the Clean Lakes Alliance, the three-day celebration, which runs through Sunday in and around The Edgewater hotel Downtown, highlights the year-round value of the area’s lakes and raises money to protect the waterways through lake improvement projects, educational programming, and water quality monitoring. Participants in a 5K run trudge through melting snow cover on the lake. Unseasonably warm weather will continue through Monday with highs in the low- to mid-40s before temperatures drop to a high in the mid-20s Tuesday.

UW's Mark Johnson shoots on Michigan State goalie Mark Mazzoleni in the third period of the Badgers' 13-3 victory over the Spartans on Jan. 6, 1979. Johnson scored three times, his fourth hat trick of the season. The three goals gave him 108 for his UW career, tying him with Bert DeHate for team's all-time lead.

UW's Mark Johnson completes a hat trick with a third-period goal past Michigan State goaltender Mark Mazzoleni while Jeffery Barr tries to defend on Jan. 6, 1979. The goal was Johnson's 108th for his Badgers career, tying him with Bert DeHate for the all-time team lead. Johnson added 17 more in his junior season for the UW record of 125 in 125 games.

The Amber Grid, 1313 University Ave., is pictured here in 1987. The bar was popular with medical workers because of its proximity to the old University Hospital. It was torn down in 2008 to build a research facility.


Wisconsin Historical Society Image 114190

The Flamingo Bar, 636 State St., was also known as the Grotto, a restaurant-bar run by Al and Mary Schiro. Patrons walked down a set of steps to the basement bar. Drinks were garnished with homemade olives. The Schiros ran the Grotto from 1949 to 1980, when it was then sold and operated as the Flamingo. The photo here was taken of the exterior in 1980. The space later became the City Bar.


Capital Times archives

You can see the Heileman's sign on Arnold's Breeze Inn, 1006 E. Washington Ave. It was torn down in 1991 to make room for a new building by a neighboring business. The Breeze Inn was operated by the Arnold family for years and was known for its juke box.


Wisconsin Historical Society property records

Joe Clementi bought the Badger Tavern, 1407 University Ave., in 1959 and ran it until 1990. The building had been the Badger Tavern since 1933, and Clementi liked the name, so he kept it. The vintage token pictured here displays the bar's address on one side and "good for 5 cents in trade" on the back.


Tokencatalog.com

Brathaus Too was located on West Mifflin Street in the 1980s. Gary “Jet” Jackson opened the second location after buying the iconic Brathaus Restaurant on State Street in the 1970s. A bar, Jet's Place, was in the basement on Mifflin.


State Journal archives

Brothers Bar & Grill, 704 University Ave., was closed in 2012 when the UW Board of Regents used its power of eminent domain to demolish the property to make way for a new music school building. Over the years, other bars operated in that spot, including Joe Hart's and the Store.


DEBORAH ZIFF - State Journal archives

Buck's Madison Square Garden occupied three different spots -- the longest being 20 years at 113 N. Hamilton St., just off Capitol Square. It was run by James "Buck" Dailey. In 2000, the moved to 802 Regent St., where it stayed until he sold the business in 2010. But Dailey launched his very first Buck's at the top of Hamilton Street in 1978, until he moved it across the street to 113 N. Hamilton two years later.

The 602 Club operated from 1951 to 1994 on University Avenue at Frances Street. Known for its eclectic customer base, the 602 drew a crowd on closing day, pictured here.


State Journal archives

Bar manager Penny Caruso (seated) and bartender Meika Alberici are behind the bar in the Lysistrata in 1978. Located at the corner of Gorham and Broom streets, it was a popular feminist and lesbian meeting spot before it was destroyed by fire in 1982.


Wisconsin Historical Society Image 67962

The Stone Front Tavern, 533 Regent St., operated in the Greenbush neighborhood and is pictured here in 1933. It was owned by Tony and Celia Schiavo.


Wisconsin Historical Society Image 6735

The interior of the Dutch Tavern, 121 N. Blount St., is shown here in 1941. In 1966, the owner moved it to 703 E. Johnson St. and changed the name to the Caribou Tavern.


Wisconsin Historical Society Image 14025

The exterior of the Black Bear Lounge, 319 N. Frances St., is shown in 1987. The bar, built in 1974, was popular but controversial for having trouble with law enforcement authorities. Owner Muriel Gervasi closed it in 1995. Eventually, the site came to house Dotty Dumplings Dowry.


Wisconsin Historical Society Image 98628

The Stone Hearth, 103 N. Park St., was part of a buzzing concert scene in Madison in the 1980s. It was a popular spot to see live music, including AC/DC, pictured here on this concert poster. Once Madison's largest nightclub, the site housed a club for 24 years, also operating as Bermuda's, R&R Station and Paramount.

Stillwaters, in business for nearly 30 years, closed in 2005. It was located at 250 State St., on the corner of State and East Johnson streets. It was a popular late-night haunt, but its restaurant also had a solid Downtown lunch crowd.


Capital Times archives

The Union House Tavern, also known as Schulkamp's Corner Saloon when this photo was taken around 1900, was at 2609 E. Washington Ave. at Milwaukee Street. Pictured here is a group of men standing on the porch holding glasses of beer. The original building was replaced, but the site operated as the Union House for decades, being replaced by the Malt House in 2008. Originally, it was part of the Union House hotel, which housed Union soldiers reporting to Camp Randall.


Wisconsin Historical Society Image 3105

The interior of the Congress Tavern, 111 W. Main St., is shown here in 1935. It was operated for many years by Pierce Nolen, drawing newspapermen and public officials, and fell victim to a fire in 1966.


Wisconsin Historical Society Image 4968

Jocko's Rocket Ship, 430 West Gilman St., was the site of a federal drug investigation that led to the indictment of nine people and allegations of drug use or sales against 11 Madison firefighters. The bar is shown here in 2000. Jocko's owner Bob Schuh, who admitted to running the bar as a drug house for 10 years, got the longest prison sentence. The bar was known as a spot to buy powder cocaine.

RILEY VETTERKIND

Bierock, 2911 N. Sherman Ave., 608-515-8087: This North Side restaurant and bar will debut heart-shaped s'more bierocks on Valentine's Day. The bierocks, or hand-held pies, will be stuffed with marshmallow, graham cracker and milk chocolate, and served with whipped cream on the side. Valentine's Day will also bring one-day-only pricing: two bierocks for $10. They normally range from $5.50 to $7. The restaurant doesn't take reservations.


AMBER ARNOLD, State Journal

The Heights, 11 N. Allen St., 608-405-5500: This new restaurant from the Underground Food Collective normally doesn't take reservations, but is accepting them for Feb. 14. The restaurant is adding Valentine's Day dishes to its regular dinner menu, including an appetizer of two seared scallops, radish cream, radish, apple, preserved lemon relish, chili and mint; and a 10-ounce aged NY strip with celery root, beef veloute, chicken liver butter and spinach. Dessert is chocolate pot de creme. Flowers will be available for purchase through a Briar Loft Valentine pop up shop and can be ordered in advance: briarloft.com/heights-pop-up.  


JOHN HART, State Journal

DelecTable in vomFASS, 3248 University Ave, 608-204-0300: DelecTable hosts dining events in an elegant yet unpretentious space in the rear of the vomFASS store. Its Valentine’s Day “Culinary Dinner Theater” called “A Feast for Love,” will extend to the Friday and Saturday nights after the holiday. The five-course meal: oysters and mignonettes, red beet soup, radicchio and red leaf salad, chateaubriand steak for two, and chocolate lava cake. The cost is $70 to $85 depending on where you sit. More details are available at delectablexp.com.


JOHN HART -- State Journal

Pasture and Plenty, 2433 University Ave., 608-665-3770: Chef Evan Dannells, formerly of Merchant and Lucille, and Edward Chwae, Ginkgo "Eat Smart" Press' executive chef, have joined Pasture and Plenty. Nate Carney is the restaurant's executive chef, and Dannells and Chwae are managing Pasture and Plenty's new evening and brunch service. They're also going to be putting on a Valentine's menu. The three-course dinner for two, with a bottle of wine (sparkling, white or red) and chocolates is $80. Omnivore or vegetarian, eat-in or to-go. Add on meals for families ($25/added portion). Customers can order online at pastureandplenty.com starting Tuesday.


AMBER ARNOLD, State Journal

Tin Fox, 2616 Monroe St., 608-709-1616: This new restaurant, which opened during the Monroe Street construction project and survived, is offering a three-course "Sweethearts Menu" for $40 (or $60 with drink pairing). The first course is either arancini (stuffed rice balls), with red sauce and basil or French onion soup with crostini, Gruyere and Swiss. The second course is red prawns with cavatelli, avocado mousse, dandelion greens, and walnut pesto; or filet Oscar, a 6-ounce filet with a potato pancake, asparagus, blue crab and béarnaise; or vegetable risotto with spaghetti squash, butternut squash, pecorino, pecans and herbs. Dessert is either flourless chocolate cake with berries and whipped cream, or salted caramel pot de creme with whipped cream and toasted almonds.


JOHN HART, State Journal

Lao Laan-Xang, 2098 Atwood Ave., 608-819-0140: The Atwood location of the Laotian restaurant will be serving complimentary SOBs, or southeast Asian Sex on the Beach. It's a longstanding Valentine's Day tradition at LLX to serve a sweet cocktail of lychee liqueur, peach schnapps, Absolut Mandrin vodka, and a mix of juices (mango, guava, lime, and cranberry). This year, the restaurant is also serving a new sticky rice heart-shaped mango dessert, which will also be free. No reservations.


M.P. KING -- State Journal

The Statehouse at the Edgewater, 1001 Wisconsin Place, 608-535-8230: Chocolate-inspired dishes from executive chef Juan Martinez will be featured for three nights  at The Statehouse. Savory dishes will include butter-poached lobster with white chocolate, caviar and champagne sauce ($18); smoked duck breast with cocoa-infused parsnips, port reduction and duck fat potatoes ($32) and Wisconsin rack of lamb with bittersweet chocolate and red wine jus, roasted tomato, raisin and poblano chili caponata ($36). Live music will begin at 8 p.m.


JOHN HART, State Journal

Tempest Oyster Bar, 120 E. Wilson St, 608-258-1443: Seafood lovers aren't the only ones in luck at Tempest this Valentine's Day. The fine dining restaurant is offering a tenderloin Oscar with king crab, asparagus and bernaise. Also look for a whole fried snapper with pomegranate syrup and kale slaw, and a cioppino with lobster, mussels, clams, calamari and scallops.


M.P. KING, STATE JOURNAL ARCHIVES

Porta Bella, 425 N. Frances St., 608-256-3186: The restaurant is celebrating Valentine's Day from Feb. 14 until Saturday, Feb. 16 with a three-course meal. Appetizer choices are calamari strips, risotto balls, stuffed mushrooms, toasted cheese ravioli, Caesar salad, or Porta Bella's signature Porta salad. Entrées include an 8-ounce top sirloin topped with portabella mushroom Marsala sauce and a crab-stuffed shell; or shrimp and scallop scampi over spinach fettuccine. Dessert is tiramisu or a toasted almond cake.


M.P. KING — State Journal archives

Chocolaterian Cafe, 6637 University Ave, Middleton, 608- 836-1156: East Siders are still mourning the loss of their beloved Atwood Avenue dessert shop and cafe. But the Middleton location is still serving Chocolaterian's famous Badger Bait and “Ugly” cookies. The cafe is hosting a Valentine's Day concert titled "Canons, Chaconnes and Chocolate" performed by the Kim/Keilson Duo and featuring musical selections from Merula, Bach, Telemann, Marais and others. Kangwon Kim on baroque violin, Lisette Keilson on recorder and special guest James Waldo on viola. Music will start at 7 p.m. and the cafe will stay open until 9 p.m. Desserts will include a chocolate cake or a vanilla passion fruit cake for two. Also expect chocolate dipped strawberries and chocolate fondue.


M.P. KING, STATE JOURNAL ARCHIVES

This simple step can prevent the arctic air from seeping into you house.
Closing the door is better for your house and your car.
Keep an electric heater or some other source of warmth in case the furnace goes out.
This can lead to carbon monoxide poisoning.

If something goes wrong and your heating system starts emitting toxic gases, you will want to know to get out of your house or have a professional fix your system.


By Tumi-1983 - Own work, CC BY-SA 3.0, https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=2944685
This prevents the lines from freezing.

Fires can start quickly, so keep external heat sources in view. If you leave a room for an extended period of time, turn them off.


By Tony Webster from Minneapolis, Minnesota, United States - Electric Space Heater, CC BY 2.0, https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=75481745

If you have a lot of snow, it is easy for furnace ventilation pipes to become blocked. Make sure these are clear to prevent dangerous gasses from entering your home.
